								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<h2>Pizza Marketing Gravitating Towards MarTech</h2><p>The investments required to follow in Domino’s footsteps may seem daunting — to aspire to forge an even more ambitious path forward may seem downright dubious — however, the prize for getting it right has already proven well worth the risk.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-22130 size-full" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Pizza-Industry-Dominos.png" alt="Line chart for International sales growth and pie charts for share of growth of SSS vs new stores" width="1011" height="668" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Pizza-Industry-Dominos.png 1011w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Pizza-Industry-Dominos-300x198.png 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Pizza-Industry-Dominos-768x507.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1011px) 100vw, 1011px" /></p><p>In 2011, Domino’s Pizza was growing by 13.5% internationally. New stores and increases in same-store sales equally accounted for that growth. In contrast, the chain grew by 16.2% in 2017, the majority (~75%) of which came from new units.</p><p>This has stimulated the pizza category chiefs to stoke their systems (and inspired other categories and segments of foodservice) with stronger marketing budgets, largely into the convergence of marketing and technology, or “MarTech.”</p><p>Based on franchisee contributions, the largest pizza chains have a marketing budget of 3.9% of sales. Quick-service companies go above and beyond this number, spending a median 4.6% of sales on marketing. Among QSR brands, some of the largest pizza chains — such as Papa John’s, Domino’s, and Little Caesars — have the heaviest marketing spend.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-22131 size-full" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-budget.jpg" alt="Bar chart with marketing spend as percentage of sales for restaurant chains" width="1009" height="670" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-budget.jpg 1009w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-budget-300x199.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-budget-768x510.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1009px) 100vw, 1009px" /></p><p>And while these companies are exerting their global ambitions, they are clear that the fight for dominance will also play out on a block-by-block, delivery-zone-by-delivery-zone basis. Pizza chains are focusing more than a third of their efforts on local-store marketing, with pizza franchisees contributing an average of 6.5% of sales to both local and national efforts.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-22132 size-full" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-for-franchisees.jpg" alt="bar chart with franchisees marketing contribution by category" width="1010" height="667" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-for-franchisees.jpg 1010w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-for-franchisees-300x198.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/pizza-marketing-for-franchisees-768x507.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1010px) 100vw, 1010px" /></p><p>These chains’ focus on marketing underlines the fact that the battle for share of stomach isn’t just about tech gadgetry. It’s also about connecting with guests to develop the kind of brand loyalty that keeps systems vibrant in the long term. Another proof point: in order to boost sales in the UK, Pizza Hut isn’t turning to promotions or discounts; they’ve hired a new marketing leader who can help develop targeted campaigns.</p>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		</div>
